The Familiar in the New Antisemitism
Why do so many Holocaust survivors sense emerging threats to Judaism, even before these threats become generally visible?
Because they know that apparently "harmless" remarks can escalate into accusations and eventually lead to discrimination that is then enshrined in law.
At this point, hysteria sets in.
The survivors sound the alarm because they know what is at stake in the game.
Damit stärken sie unsere Demokratien auf eine Weise, wie nur sie es können.
Wir hören den Überlebenden zu, damit auch wir überleben.
Seit der ersten Runde der Präsidentschaftswahlen in Frankreich steht fest, dass wir allen Grund haben, zuzuhören.
Aber nicht nur Demagogen wie Jean Marie Le Pen oder andere ungehobelte Rechtsextremisten in Europa verursachen Schwierigkeiten.
Im 20. Jahrhundert wurden aus Menschen, die sich selbst als "Intellektuelle" sahen, oftmals Trittbrettfahrer des Faschismus oder Kommunismus, ohne dass sie sich einer Partei mit dem entsprechendem ideologischen Hintergrund anschlossen.
In the 21st century, we are dealing with people - with the "educated bourgeoisie" in connection with the mass media, politics, government, and universities - who condemn Israel in a language that often reminds one of that used by foot soldiers of these antidemocratic movements.
This is not the majority opinion in the Western world - not yet, thankfully - but it is the voice of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, the example of the French ambassador to Britain should be mentioned: recently, he dubbed Israel during a dinner party in London as "this damned little country."
His vulgar language is not particularly alarming.
What is alarming, however, are the reactions to it.
He was not recalled by his government, nor did the Blair government demand his recall. In the public sphere, the matter was dismissed as just another scandal.
The French press portrayed the ambassador as a victim of British petty manners, rather than of his own contemptible attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador in Britain has several allies among Europe's elites.
Ambassador Bernard nevertheless did us a service: through him, it became clear how widespread these new anti-Jewish sentiments are.
As a columnist put it so aptly: Israel has become a target of hatred, whose name one dares not utter.
We are not only allowed to say it, we are even obliged to say it.
Given the daily attacks on Jews and synagogues in France, we must not remain silent.
It is a disgrace for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without worrying about their safety.
Antisemitic attacks are also reported elsewhere. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, and parts of Eastern Europe.
We must not remain silent about the fact that the denial of the Holocaust has become commonplace. Nor must we remain silent about the comparisons that antisemites and anti-Zionists draw between Israel and the Third Reich.
While in a Palestinian television program Israeli soldiers are portrayed as rapists and cold-blooded murderers, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we "must confront the new Nazi plague that is emerging in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It is not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. One hates them almost everywhere."
During a televised Friday prayer broadcast on Palestinian television, the preacher urged Muslims to "show no mercy to the Jews. No matter where you are, kill them and these Americans who are just like them."
What we should think about in connection with antisemitism is that it always begins with the Jews, but never ends with the Jews.
If the hatred of Jews is not checked, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against antisemitism is therefore the task of Jews as well as non-Jews.
At the moment, the points of attack in this fight are blurrier than ever before, because an astonishing aspect of today's antisemitism is its flexibility.
Although the goal of antisemitism has always remained the same - namely to attack the Jews - it nevertheless changes its appearance, its strategy, its rationalizations, and even its vocabulary.
Once, the Jewish religion was the target.
When this did not yield results, the Jews were expelled or killed.
When in the 19th century the theory of race captivated people, Jews were attacked because of their belonging to a bad race.
With the existence of the state of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, Zionism is today slandered as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with antisemitism.
Just as with other nations, it is entirely legitimate to critically oppose certain political strategies and decisions of Israel.
Anti-Zionism is, however, becoming increasingly similar to antisemitism.
Anti-Zionists sometimes claim that they are not against the Jews, but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I am only against the existence of Great Britain, but I am not anti-British!"
Or if someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
You would not believe them.
It is difficult to love or respect a people, but to hate their state.
Yet there are people in connection with Israel who claim to be able to do exactly that.
In various UN organizations, insults against Israel are routine.
This demonization of the only democratic system of government in the Near East is a core aspect of this new antisemitism.
When Israel is described as "the enemy of all good and the source of all evil," then within the UN the "doctrine of contempt" circulates, as expressed by Professor Irwin Cotler, a member of Canada's Parliament.
This constant portrayal of a nation as the enemy of humanity is in truth a campaign against the Jewish people.
So liegen den zahlreichen anti-jüdischen Übergriffen in vielen Ländern die Verteufelungen Israels zugrunde, die sich einer antisemitischen Terminologie bedienen.
Attacken auf Synagogen werden oftmals durch die Verwendung dieser verleumderischen Sprache im Zusammenhang mit dem Nahen Osten ausgelöst.
Im Vergleich zu früheren anti-jüdischen Ausbrüchen, handelt es sich bei dem heutigen Antisemitismus weniger um Angriffe auf einzelne Juden, als vielmehr um eine Attacke gegen den "kollektiven Juden", also gegen den Staat Israel.
Derartige Attacken haben aber eine Kettenreaktion von Übergriffen auf einzelne Juden und jüdische Institutionen in ganz Europa und Lateinamerika in Gang gesetzt.
Früher waren die gefährlichsten Antisemiten diejenigen, die die Welt judenrein machen wollten.
The most dangerous antisemites today are those who want to make the world free of Jewish states.
